 The Gnamma Hole tenement lies some 35 kilometres Southwest of Davyhurst in the 
 Coolgardie  Mineral  Field  of  WA.    It  is  located  in  the  north  western  part  of  the

 7.0  WORK CARRIED OUT THIS REPORTING YEAR 
 The area has not seen any activity for over 15 years and any tracks that previously 
 existed were totally overgrown and inaccessible.  A considerable amount of clearing 
 was required to gain access to and though the tenement. 
 A search of open file records indicating previous exploration was carried out without 
 Field  reconnaissance  was  completed  to  verify  the  lack  of  previous  exploration 
 activities although very thick bush prevented extensive coverage.  Further extensive 
 clearing  will  need  to  be  undertaken  before  further  planned  work  such  as  ground 
 magnetics, auger sampling and RAB drilling can be carried out next field season. 
 Geological field inspection of the project area targeted the central part of the tenement 
 where very sparse low outcrop and aeromagnetic interpretation indicates the possibly 
 of a small greenstone belt beneath sand plain cover which has had only rudimentary 
 examination by prospectors in the past. 
 Earlier  reconnaissance  had  shown  that  existing  access  tracks  to  the  tenement  were 
 disused  and  heavily  overgrown,  both  from  the  south,  from  the  Great  Eastern 
 Highway, and from the northeast.  A local contractor was therefore engaged re-open 
 selected portions from the northeast with a front-end loader, starting from the Callion 
 minesite area on the Davyhurst road.
